	shorttitle = {Clendenin, West Virginia},
	abstract = {Today’s enormous petrochemical industry is built on a technology that began modestly in the hills of West Virginia. In 1920, the Carbide and Carbon Chemicals Corporation was formed as a subsidiary of the Union Carbide and Carbon Company. It was established to develop a process to manufacture ethylene, which could then be converted into several industrially useful compounds. The move to ethylene was a revolutionary step because acetylene was the workhorse chemical of the day.},
